div.p:
Therefore not without verie good cause doth the notable writer (I recited in the beginning of this treatise) lay downe in the very first chapter of his booke the daunger and inconueniences that grow to men for lacke of consideration, vsing also in another place among many his diuine similitudes this one, that men are caried by inconsideration to their euerlasting ruine without any striuing;
                  Simile.
               euen as Hawkes are caried hooded verie quietly, which if their sight were free, would neuer leaue bating till they had broken their lines, or vtterly tyred themselues: but notwithstanding that the Ring of Reason maketh him discerne these foule deformities of Alcyna, yet it is maruellous to see what wonderfull impediments be set in his way ere he can discharge himselfe of his late received mistresse.
